        "references": [
            "Table 1 summarizes key contributions of our work relative to the most closely related literature in centralized and decentralized FL. To the best of our knowledge, our work is the first to consider sporadic SGDs and aggregations simultaneously in the fully decentralized (i.e., serverless) setting. The last three columns in the table are properties of our analysis. Our analysis provides convergence guarantees for last iterates, as opposed to average iterates over all time, under milder assumptions on data heterogeneity and graph connectivity than existing works, as we will elaborate in Sec. 4.\nWe organize the rest of this section around the two dimensions of sporadicity in DFL which DSpodFL integrates.",
            "In Assumption 4.1-(c), we do not make the stricter assumption of ζ=0𝜁0\\zeta=0 that is found in some works discussed in Table 1. The addition of this proximal term makes our bounds tighter and causes our theoretical analysis to be more conclusive (Lin et al., 2021).",
            "Assumption 4.3 is milder than similar assumptions made in existing works, e.g., considering a static connected graph (Mishchenko et al., 2022; Sun et al., 2022; Wang & Nedic, 2022) or a B𝐵B-connected graph (Nedic & Ozdaglar, 2009). See Table 1 for a further comparison to these works.",
            "We also note that Eqs. (9) and (10) are derived for the consensus error and the average model error themselves, i.e., their last iterates. As summarized in Table 1, this is an improvement over existing works with sporadic aggregations (Koloskova et al., 2020; Lian et al., 2017; Sundhar Ram et al., 2010) where only the Cesaro sums (i.e., the running averages of the iterates) of these error terms are bounded."
        ]
